<font color="#FF0000">AN INVITATION.....</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan 26 15:16:16 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dear Mr. Ratliff (John) and other readers of this &quot;dialog string&quot;<br><br>
Many thanks for your recommendation. Will check out the book this weekend at the UCD library.....<br><br>
We had our third meeting last Thursday evening, a total of five speakers; during the last two hours of the seminar each speaker interacted with each of the student work teams and answered questions posed by the students.<br><br>
Speakers covered a very broad range of issues, among them: background to understanding the Communist Party as it evolved in Southeast Asia; the domino theory and the lesson of Munich; the siege and defeat of the French at Dien Pien Phu; issues associated with elections and exchange of populations that arose at the Geneva Convention; Cold War politics viz. America, the Soviets, and China; changing political views in America during the 1950s, 1960s, and 1970s; differential views towards French and Japanese occupation of Viet Nam (as perceived by the Americans and by the Vietnamese, themselves); historical differences between the peoples of northern and southern Viet Nam and how these differences continue to be manifest today in 1997; differential perspectives on American involvement in Viet Nam from a former U.S. Navy Intelligence Officer, from a West Point graduate, from a Vietnamese intellectual, and from a participant in the anti-war peace movement in the United States.<br><br>
Each week the seminar students write about their team activities, personal research efforts, and their thoughts-impressions-feelings about the course.  This is done via e-mail. <br><br>
I have been a professor since 1976.... In all these years, I have never experienced such excitement in the classroom. There is such an eagerness and willingness to learn, to become involved in interviews, &quot;web-surfing,&quot; to participate further in learning about Viet Nam.  These 19 students: what a fine group!<br><br>
On behalf of my students, I extend the invitation to all readers of this dialog string.... if you wish to be interviewed via e-mail, post your e-mail or FAX number at this site, or at the following:<br><br>
legrivetti@ucdavis.edu<br><br>
We look forward to hearing from you.
